<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>What are the three main goals of macroeconomic policy?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Economic growth, full employment, and price stability</option>
            <option letter="b">Maximum profits, minimum unemployment, and zero inflation</option>
            <option letter="c">Budget surplus, trade surplus, and monetary stability</option>
            <option letter="d">High wages, low taxes, and balanced trade</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The three main goals of macroeconomic policy are economic growth (increasing real GDP), full employment (minimizing cyclical unemployment), and price stability (maintaining low and stable inflation).</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>During which phase of the business cycle does real GDP growth become negative?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Peak</option>
            <option letter="b">Recession</option>
            <option letter="c">Trough</option>
            <option letter="d">Recovery</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>During a recession, real GDP growth becomes negative as economic activity contracts. This period is characterized by declining output, employment, and income levels.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>In the circular flow model, which of the following represents a leakage from the circular flow?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Consumer spending</option>
            <option letter="b">Government purchases</option>
            <option letter="c">Savings</option>
            <option letter="d">Wages</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>Savings represents a leakage from the circular flow because it is income that is not immediately spent on goods and services. The other major leakages are taxes and imports.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Real GDP is calculated by:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Multiplying nominal GDP by the GDP deflator</option>
            <option letter="b">Dividing nominal GDP by the GDP deflator and multiplying by 100</option>
            <option letter="c">Adding the GDP deflator to nominal GDP</option>
            <option letter="d">Subtracting the GDP deflator from nominal GDP</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Real GDP is calculated by dividing nominal GDP by the GDP deflator (expressed as a decimal) and multiplying by 100. This process removes the effects of price changes to show actual economic growth.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
